Step 1a: Planning¶

Identify the information in the file your program will read¶

1) Economic factors per country

  • includes unemployment_rate, gdp_per_cap, and gov_type columns.

2) Self reported happiness scores per country

  • includes total Happiness Score and individual factors that add up to that total; Economy (GDP per Capita), Family, Health (Life Expectancy), Freedom, Trust (Government Corruption), Generosity, Dystopia Residual columns.

3) Omitted information (not intended to be used in my first choice program)

  • includes countrys' Region, Happiness Rank, Happiness Score, Lower Confidence Interval, Upper Confidence Interval columns.

Step 1b: Planning¶

Brainstorm ideas for what your program will produce¶

Select the idea you will build on for subsequent steps¶

1) How economic factors affect happiness ratings (first choice)

  • First the funciton will analyze the countries economic data and sort the countries according to the reader's desired input:
    • unemployment rate margins: <= 2%, 2.1 - 4%, 4.1 - 6%, 6.1 - 8%, 8.1 - 10%, 10.1 - 12%, 12.1 - 14%, 14.1 - 16%, 16.1 - 18%, 18.1 - 20%, >20.1% (11 groups)
    • GDP per capita margins: <=100k, 99.9k - 50k, 49.9k - 20k, 19.9k - 10k, 9.9k - 5k, 4.9k - 1k, >1k (7 groups)
    • government types: consitutional monarchy, absolute monarchy, repblic, communist state (4 groups)
  • In each group, a second function will add up the desired happiness scores of the countries collected (also chosen by the reader; i.e. total happiness or individual factors) and calculate the avergage per group (output).
  • The result will look like a bar graph comparing how/if economic factors affect people's happiness.
    • Possible cases:
      • Unemployment rate vs. health score average
      • GDP per capita vs. total happiness average
      • Governemnt type vs. trust in government average
    • Any data missing from either the input or the output will be ommited from the count because

2) Happiness score versus region

  • For each region, calculate the average happiness score.
  • Reader will input the regions they want to compare.
  • Creates a bar graph

3) Value of Happiness Scores per country

  • Create a pie chart to represent a country's value of happiness factors.
  • Economy (GDP per Capita), Family, Health (Life Expectancy), Freedom, Trust (Government Corruption), Generosity, and Dystopia Residual all add up to a country's total happiness (happiness factors).
  • One function will calculate the percentage of the happiness factors and another will display them in a visualization.
  • Reader can input whatever country they want to see, and the output demonstrates what a country values most in terms of their happiness.

from typing import List, NamedTuple, Optional
from cs103 import *

EconFactor = NamedTuple('EconFactor', [('name', str),
                                       ('unemployment_rate', Optional[float]),
                                       ('gdp_per_cap', Optional[int]),
                                       ('gov_type', str)])

# interp. the economic factors of a country by its unemployment rate, 
# GDP per capita, and governemnt type (gov_type)

EF_AUSTRALIA = EconFactor('Australia', 5.8, 45514, "Constitutional monarchy")
EF_TURKMENISTAN = EconFactor('Turkmenistan', 3.5, 16499, 'Republic')

# template based on compound
@typecheck
def fn_for_econ_factor(ef: EconFactor) -> ...:
    return... (ef.name, 
               ef.unemployment_rate,
               ef.gdp_per_cap,
               ef.gov_type)


HappyScore = NamedTuple('HappyScore', [('name', str),
                                       ('total_happy', Optional[float]),
                                       ('gdp_score', Optional[float]),
                                       ('family', Optional[float]),
                                       ('health', Optional[float]),
                                       ('freedom', Optional[float]),
                                       ('trust', Optional[float]),
                                       ('generosity', Optional[float]),
                                       ('dystopia', Optional[float])])

# interp. the happiness scores of a country by its total happiness ('total_happy'), 
# economy/GDP per capita (gdp_score), family, health/life expectancy ('health'), freedom, 
# trust in government ('trust'), generosity, and dystopia residual ('dystopia').

HS_DENMARK = HappyScore('Denmark', 7.526, 1.44178, 1.16374, 0.79504, 0.57941, 0.44453, 0.36171, 2.73939)
HS_ZIMBABWE = HappyScore('Zimbabwe', 4.193, 0.35041, 0.71478, 0.1595, 0.25429, 0.08582, 0.18503, 2.4427)

# template based on compound
@typecheck
def fn_for_happy_score(hs: HappyScore) -> ...:
    return... (hs.name, 
               hs.total_happy,
               hs.gdp_score,
               hs.family,
               hs.health,
               hs.freedom,
               hs.trust,
               hs.generosity,
               hs.dystopia)

def fn_for_loef(loef: List[EconFactor]) -> ...:
    # description of the acc

import csv

@typecheck
def read_x(fn: str) -> List[EconFactor]:
    """
    reads information from the specified file (fn) and returns a list of EconFactor data   
    """
    
    # return [] #stub
    # template from HtDAP
    # loef contains the result so far
    with open(fn) as csvfile:
        reader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        loef = [] # type: List[EconFactor]
        next(reader) # skip header line

        for row in reader:
            ef = EconFactor(row[0],
                            parse_float(row[13]),
                            parse_int(row[14]),
                            row[15])
            loef.append(ef)
    
    return loef

@typecheck
def read_y(fn: str) -> List[HappyScore]:
    """
    reads information from the specified file (fn) and returns a list of HappyScore data   
    """
    
    # return [] #stub
    # template from HtDAP
    # lohs contains the result so far
    with open(fn) as csvfile:
        reader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        lohs = [] # type: List[HappyScore]
        next(reader) # skip header line

        for row in reader:
            hs = HappyScore(row[0], 
                            parse_float(row[3]),
                            parse_float(row[6]), 
                            parse_float(row[7]), 
                            parse_float(row[8]),
                            parse_float(row[9]),
                            parse_float(row[10]),
                            parse_float(row[11]),
                            parse_float(row[12]))
            lohs.append(hs)
        
    return lohs

start_testing()

expect(read_x('happy.v.econ(test1).csv'), [EconFactor('Australia', 5.8, 45514, 'Constitutional monarchy'),
                                          EconFactor('Turkmenistan', 3.5, 16499, 'Republic')])

                                           HappyScore('Zimbabwe', 4.193, 0.35041, 0.71478, 0.1595, 0.25429, 0.08582, 0.18503, 2.4427)])
